  <p>
    Now that we have defined vectors,
    and have created a nice notation by which to describe them,
    we start considering how vectors interact with each other.
    That is, we define an <em>algebra</em> on vectors.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def_vector_algebra">
    <title>Vector Algebra</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>\vec u = \la u_1,u_2\ra</m> and
              <m>\vec v = \la v_1,v_2\ra</m> be vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>,
              and let <m>c</m> be a scalar.
              <idx><h>vectors</h><h>algebra of</h></idx>
            </p>

            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The addition, or sum,
                    of the vectors <m>\vec u</m> and <m>\vec v</m> is the vector
                    <me>
                      \vec u+\vec v = \la u_1+v_1, u_2+v_2\ra
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    The multiplication of a scalar <m>c</m> and a vector <m>\vec v</m> is the vector
                    <me>
                      c\vec v = c\la v_1,v_2\ra = \la cv_1,cv_2\ra
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>\vec u = \la u_1,u_2,u_3\ra</m> and
              <m>\vec v = \la v_1,v_2,v_3\ra</m> be vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>,
              and let <m>c</m> be a scalar.
            </p>

            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The addition, or sum,
                    of the vectors <m>\vec u</m> and <m>\vec v</m> is the vector
                    <me>
                      \vec u+\vec v = \la u_1+v_1, u_2+v_2, u_3+v_3\ra
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    The multiplication of a scalar <m>c</m> and a vector <m>\vec v</m> is the vector
                    <me>
                      c\vec v = c\la v_1,v_2,v_3\ra = \la cv_1,cv_2,cv_3\ra
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    In short, we say addition and scalar multiplication are computed
    <q>component-wise.</q>
  </p>

